snippet.textDisplay:
Today's economy was already bonkers even before COVID; the entirety of my retirement savings that I started on in my early twenties would maybe last me a year if I were unbelievably frugal. I'm excluding any potential pension fund and disregarding the fact that I'm just 36 and still have some time to go, but even then I find myself understanding why a good chunk of my coworkers are folks in their sixties clocking in for a sideline.


It's not just millennials who can't retire; NOBODY can afford to retire. Add medical costs to it all and it's really no wonder these same colleagues hoard sick days and pinch pennies. Plug COVID into the equation, and you're left with the demonstrable fact that unemployment benefits just cannot cover base living expenses. I say that as a Canadian, so this is a global problem, and not just endemic to America.


Eat the rich, indeed.

snippet.textDisplay:
For anyone wondering if you should have the same existential crisis:

Brian's data discounted 401ks and Roth/Traditional IRAs. He gave the Universe's greatest power - compounding interest - to the forces working against you(Inflation) and made no effort to calculate its effect in your favor - such as would be in almost any appreciating asset... such as a 401k, IRA, or even a regular savings account.

This means that in Brian's math, your money grows linearly, while the money needed for retirement grows exponentially. With that in mind, it's really not surprising that it cranked out some horrifying numbers.

They are your odds if you let your savings sit there, doing nothing.

Money you have should never do nothing; it should be fighting for you even when you aren't.

snippet.textDisplay: You should do an Unraveled looking in to what determines which animals in Animal Crossing get to be sentient cartoon people and which are realistic animals in the critter category and can be sold and put in museums and such. At first glance it seems as simple as "tetrapods = sentient cartoons, everything else = critters" but there are a few problems, including amphibians (there are frogs/tadpoles in the "fish" category, but also frog and salamander villagers and NPCs) and cephalopods (which again are represented both in the critter and villager categories). It gets even more complicated if you consider the many tetrapods among the fossils (which, while there's no indication either way w.r.t. sentience, are depicted realistically, which is consistent with critters; further if they were sentient there'd be some rather messy cultural heritage concerns with selling them to the shops), though it's possible whatever happened to uplift the various animals to sentience happened in (geologically) recent history...

snippet.textDisplay:
Mario doesn't necessarily have to visit every level only once. He could just go back to NSMB2's levels between games.


Also, you can't really use Superstar Saga as a reference considering those are Beanbean Kingdom coins, not Mushroom Kingdom coins. It's outright stated before the game's second boss that they use separate currencies and as a result, have separate exchange rates. Since Mushroom coins are worth significantly-less-enough coins that they don't reach the 100-coin toll of Beanbean coins, we can assume that the Beanbean Kingdom has only ever been in turmoil during the events of that game, rather than the head of state being kidnapped and smuggled to another kingdom's capital every four months.


Hell, you may not even be able to use ANY game as a reference, considering there's always a vaguely-political crisis happening during every game in which you can buy items. Main-series platformers, either Peach is kidnapped or another kingdom is invading. RPGs, either Peach is kidnapped or there's an ancient evil threatening the entire world. Mario Party, all the unauthorized construction of life-size board game boards, that in every intro cutscene since Mario Party 4, manages to surprise everyone INCLUDING Peach and Daisy. The sports games? All the god-damn funding that goes into setting up the events. The Tokyo Olympics alone is estimated at $12.6 billion. Not to mention that the planning for Mario Sports Mix was all carried out in less than a week, as the elemental crystals fell from the sky at night and were each split into three pieces to sit in the cores of different trophies as prizes for four separate sports, either the next morning or a few days later. Each Olympics begins planning, at the very least, immediately after they finalize preparations for the previous one, perhaps even the one before it. That's where all the $12.6 billion went. Now imagine the kind of budget you'd need to arrange an event in 7 days.
And that is still not even counting their own attendance AT each Olympics since Beijing, alongside Sonic and everyone attending with him. They probably have to add extra costs to that $12.6 billion for the Tokyo Olympics, not to mention the damages caused by everything Bowser, Eggman, and Eggman Nega do at each Olympics, especially this year's flat-out disappearance of their biggest representatives/stars after being sucked into the Tokyo64. Hell, Bowser and Eggman rarely ever even remember to APPLY TO REGISTER at each Olympics, meaning their last-second attendance pushes each event over-budget, especially the years when Eggman Nega is present, as he shows up usually halfway through the event or right at the end.


There will never be a time when you can properly calculate the value of a coin, because it'll always be during either a time where the most important people in the nation are in danger, or a time of massive government spending, both of which heavily damage its value, whether by increase or decrease, because the amount it gets increased or decreased is so extreme in so short a time.
Don't even get me started on how plausible the recent COVID-19 Game Theory is, considering Mario and Sonic's attendance at the Tokyo Olympics. That will likely cause the most damage in the Mushroom Kingdom's history, considering it would only ever be the second outbreak that ever showed up there, after the Blorbs which was engineered by Fawful. They are not prepared to fight pandemics, as there's been so few that they have never needed to learn how to prepare, or been able to study any samples. It's just such a healthy world. Sure, there's at least three common viruses in the Mushroom Kingdom, but they only cause fevers and/or chills and there's insta-cures readily available for them, so they don't count. Even if all of the most notable figures in the kingdom manage to survive (which, they have Plot Armor so they will), there's very little hope once they rid the kingdom of COVID-19 as millions of other, generic, nameless individuals in the populous will have been claimed (at least except for Toads, as those specific masks mentioned in the theory fit on their faces).


The mere fact that a fair amount of luxury items are still fairly cheap even during times of crisis, still points to the fact that this economy will never collapse. However, it will never be predictable, it will never be fair on the average citizen, it will never be fair on the government, it will never be fair on the military, and it will never, ever, EVER be able to be compared to any other economy. And above all else, no one will ever be able to retire, whatsoever.
